The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance launched a gene research that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research in order to identify the gene responsible for children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research aimed at discovering a gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research called "Genetic obesity in children and young people" will be able to obtain results regarding overweight.
In a report by the Research Medical Unit in the field of biochemistry from the specialized hospital of the National Health Centre of the 21st century, Miguel Cruz López explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition experts and social workers was established.
This team is supported by experts and students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
Joining the research can also be a wide public, with or without authorization. People can come to the IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where they will conduct tests with young people every 8 hours.
He stressed that the research started at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexico State) and since 8 October this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Centre (East Mexico State).
Once data are obtained from 500 children to 600 children, the study will continue at the Sport Centre of Independentia (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Sport Centre Morelos (south of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for children and young people in Mexico and thus prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of Diabetes, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to gather data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 with the consent and supervision of parents for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also be asked about the physical activity and family history of inherited diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause disease such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He explained that an anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist), blood pressure are measured, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined every Saturday, and genes are tested (an attempt is made to identify genes that participate in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research reflects the concerns of the health care professionals about the alarming increase in the child’s weight.
'Health surveys carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was only 77% obesity among boys and 47% among girls. There was also a dramatic increase in overweight,' said IMSS expert.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the belief that the country's population differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African.
He explained that the general genetics of obesity are usually explained as inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of participants is that they will receive an overall assessment of the state of the children, which will determine whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He pointed out that even the presence of acantosis (acantosis) on the neck and the forehead suggests that the individual is likely to suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diarrhoea conditions.
The information is confidential so far, doctors hand it over in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and changes in life - style that they have to make in order for their children to avoid disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life that means a lack of daily physical activity, full-day sitting before television and using means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
The excess also causes a large caloric intake, which is greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tumbles, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic burden, which is the subject of this research.
