Nord Stream, new port of entry for Russian gas to Europe
The remote North Stream pipeline connecting directly Eastern Europe to Russia and led by the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to function.
Must add gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas station, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the launch of the North Stream last Tuesday, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitrij Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together to control the Russian gas supply valve into the Western European network.
This new pipeline will start to flow to Western Europe 27.5 billion additional cubic metres of Russian gas by the first pipeline of 1,224 km long connecting Petrograd region with the Mecklenburg-Pomorjana society.
The second pipeline to be completed by the end of 2012 will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, which is the quantity equal to all French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility to build the third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested against the project.
Nord Stream will in fact be able to deliver gas directly to Germany without being run by any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
In turn, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of putting pressure on Russia at risk of closing its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
The strongest expression was made by Warsaw when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", with the withdrawal of the alliance between Hitler and Stalin in the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means that it is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases by supporting this Russian project.
But it is worth the price of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created gaps between Europe from the east and the west.
Russia has barely succeeded in establishing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries with high gas consumption, whose deposits are approaching its end.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new hub that connects us organically," said François Fillon at the celebration of the opening of this pipeline and demonstrated the point at which large gas contracts are both politically and economically.
All this explains the broad smiles of the leaders of Gazprom present in large numbers in Lubmin, the lead gas station.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The seabed tube is made of steel fitted with a concrete coating to protect it from the waves of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During his construction, he had to avoid the mines of World War II.
"For their safety, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, a spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to impose measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube itself is a long metal snake weighing 242 Eiffelovek, which has not been interrupted in its entire length by valves or maintenance stations.
A control panel was to be built near Sweden, but the leading project rejected it when the Swedes were only a little eager to see the Russian state company, as it was settled on their coast.
"In the event of a dispute, we will stop the flow of gas in less than 1 minute," explains Jens Müller.
In case of uncertainty, the gas contained in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the authors because the answers were designed to cause anxiety once in 100,000 years.
The control of the external position of the pipeline shall be carried out by an underwater robot towed by a vessel while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device circulating inside.
This 1-metre-shaped device is inserted into the tube and is compressed with gas.
In order to complete the three-day journey at 3 m/s, it shall provide accurate information on possible metal parts distortions.
The remote gas pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to be less repair.
Gas circulation is simply secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the end.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains in Gazprom, which holds a 51% share.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunia and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream entrusted with the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company has a residence in the city of Zoug, Switzerland, where tax is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently rented this company for a five-year contract, which can be renewed, all its gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will have a profit from total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the pipeline was secured by 30% of the shareholders and by 70% of the bank loans.
The total labour costs should be €7.4 billion for both pipes.
For the GDF Suez group, investment costs amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be reimbursed, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline comes from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy shore with pine forests.
The valves at a height of 4.5 meters form an exit gate of gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the coming gas before being transported to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is achieved, this will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
