The study conducted in April of the association IMS-Entreprerre pour la Cité found that survey managers have a "weak level of knowledge about disabled persons" with an "excessive idea of people on the wheelchair and mental or mental disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the target of 6% of disabled workers laid down in the 1987 Act.
The last known figures from 2008 indicate a status of 2.6%.
"Now we are moving around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, responsible for collecting fees from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence is the number of "scattered" companies, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 companies to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates true awareness, especially in large businesses."
